# 🚀 Creating a Thread

Java provides two ways:

## 1️⃣ Extending Thread Class

```java id="lyrjkg"
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is Running...");
    }

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();

        t1.start();

    }
}
```

### Output

```text id="wl7xhf"
Thread is Running...
```

---

## 2️⃣ Implementing Runnable Interface

```java id="9gbnnt"
class MyThread implements Runnable {

    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is Running...");
    }

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Thread t1 = new Thread(new MyThread());

        t1.start();

    }
}
```

---

# ⭐ Difference Between start() and run()

| start()               | run()                         |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| Creates a new thread  | Executes like a normal method |
| JVM manages execution | No new thread created         |

```java id="tvjlwm"
Thread t = new MyThread();

t.start();
```

---

# 🏃 Multiple Threads Example

```java id="k0g1yy"
class MyThread extends Thread {

    public void run() {

        for(int i=1; i<=5; i++) {
            System.out.println(i);
        }

    }

}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t1 = new MyThread();
        MyThread t2 = new MyThread();

        t1.start();
        t2.start();

    }
}
```

